---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Playwright training — grimbergIT"
  description="Playwright workshops — cross-browser coverage and deeper context for teams that need it."
>
  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 03</p>
    <h1>Playwright</h1>

    <p>
      Playwright fits teams who need cross-browser coverage. It also fits when the boring plumbing
      must be part of the design: auth flows, network interception, tracing across contexts. The
      workshop starts with the primitives, then moves quickly into real code against a real
      application.
    </p>

    <h2>What we cover</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        The Playwright programming model: architecture, primitives, and the parts that shape how you
        write tests.
      </li>
      <li>
        Multiple browsers, multiple contexts, and multi-user flows: the situations Playwright exists
        for.
      </li>
      <li>
        Network interception, route stubbing, and the tracing tools that make debugging cheap.
      </li>
      <li>Component and API test modes: when they replace an end-to-end, and when they don't.</li>
      <li>CI patterns for parallelism, shards, and staying under the flake threshold.</li>
      <li>
        For teams evaluating or migrating from another framework: where Playwright diverges, and how
        to think about the differences. No religious wars required.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One day by default. Splittable into two half-days if the team's calendar prefers it. Also
      available as a multi-week cohort with homework in between. In-house or remote — either works.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      A working test setup against your own application. The CI configuration to run it. Plus enough
      judgement about Playwright versus anything else that the next framework debate is a shorter
      conversation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <a href="/training/">← Back to training</a> ·
      <a href="/contact">Book a session →</a>
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
